dels (GCMs) forced with increasing greenhouse gas concentrations predict enhanced atmospheric moisture transports to the high northern latitudes. Together with melting of Arctic sea ice and glaciers, this has led to the expectation of a gradual freshening of the northern North Atlantic, tending to reduce the strength of the Atlantic Meridional Overturning Circulation (AMOC). Here a multi-member greenhouse gas GCM experiment is used to demonstrate that both the salinity in the North Atlantic and the inflow of Atlantic Water to the Nordic Seas may increase despite a strong freshening of the Arctic Ocean and a reduced AMOC. Copyright 2006 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Glaciers; Global warming; Greenhouse gases; Saline water; Atlantic Meridional Overturning Circulation (AMOC); Atmospheric moisture; General circulation models (GCM); Climatology; atmosphere-ocean coupling; atmospheric moisture; global warming; greenhouse gas; inflow; meridional circulation; moisture transfer; oceanic general circulation model; sea surface salinity; Arctic Ocean; Atlantic Ocean; Atlantic Ocean (North); Norwegian Sea",,,,,,"Aagaard, K., Carmack, E.C., The role of sea ice and other fresh water in the Arctic circulation (1989) J. Geophys. Res, 94 (C10), pp. 14,485-14,498; Bentsen, M., Drange, H., Furevik, T., Zhou, T., Simulated variability of the Atlantic meridional overturning circulation (2004) Clim. Dyn, 22, pp. 701-720; Boyer, T.P., Levitus, S., Antonov, J.I., Locarnini, R.A., Garcia, H.E., Linear trends in salinity for the World Ocean, 1955-1998 (2005) Geophys. Res. Lett, 32, pp. L01604. , doi:10.1029/2004GL021791; Bryden, H.L., Longworth, H.R., Cunningham, S.A., Slowing of the Atlantic meridional overturning circulation at 25° (2005) Nature, 438, pp. 655-657. , doi:10.1038/nature04385; Collins, M., Interannual to decadal climate predictability in the North Atlantic: A multimodel-ensemble study (2006) J. Clim, 19, pp. 1195-1203; Covey, C., AchutaRao, K.M., Cubasch, U., Jones, P.